<div class="guidance-container">
    <div class="guidance-header">What to Do When Someone Dies in Islam</div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>1. Pronounce the Statement of Faith (Shahadah)</h3>
        <p>If present at the time of death, encourage the dying person to say <strong>“La ilaha illallah”</strong> (There is no god but Allah). If the person passes away, say:</p>
        <p><em>“Inna lillahi wa inna ilayhi raji'oon”</em> (Indeed, to Allah we belong and to Him we shall return) – <strong>Qur’an 2:156</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>2. Close the Eyes and Cover the Body</h3>
        <p>After the person has passed away:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Close their eyes gently.</li>
            <li>Bind the jaw if needed to keep it closed.</li>
            <li>Straighten the arms and legs.</li>
            <li>Cover the entire body with a clean sheet.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>3. Inform the Family and Loved Ones</h3>
        <p>Notify close relatives and friends so they can offer prayers, support, and make necessary arrangements. Avoid loud crying or wailing, as this is discouraged in Islam.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>4. Contact the Local Mosque or Cemetery Authority</h3>
        <p>Get in touch with CCM (Connecticut Council of Masajid) or the Islamic Center of Hamden (ICH) to begin burial preparations. Fill out the online burial registration form or speak to a representative directly.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>5. Ghusl (Washing the Body)</h3>
        <p>The deceased must be washed (ghusl) according to Islamic guidelines:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Performed by Muslims of the same gender.</li>
            <li>Washed an odd number of times (typically three).</li>
            <li>Private parts must be covered at all times.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This should be done with modesty, cleanliness, and care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>6. Kafan (Shrouding the Body)</h3>
        <p>Wrap the deceased in white, plain cloth (kafan):</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Men are shrouded in 3 pieces of cloth.</li>
            <li>Women are shrouded in 5 pieces of cloth.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>7. Salat al-Janazah (Funeral Prayer)</h3>
        <p>This prayer is performed in congregation without bowing or prostration. It is a collective obligation (fard kifayah) upon the Muslim community.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>8. Burial (Dafn)</h3>
        <p>The body should be transported to the cemetery and buried as soon as possible. At Paradise Avenue Muslim Cemetery:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Burial is done during daylight only.</li>
            <li>Body is laid on its right side facing the Qiblah.</li>
            <li>Dua and supplications are made after burial.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="guidance-section">
        <h3>9. Making Dua and Giving Sadaqah</h3>
        <p>Pray for the deceased, asking Allah for mercy and forgiveness. Sadaqah Jariyah (ongoing charity), good deeds, and du’a from righteous children benefit the deceased.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="note-box">
        <strong>Note:</strong> This guide is based on established teachings from the Qur’an and authentic Hadith. For specific cases, consult your local imam or CCM/ICH representative.
    </div>
